<p>Most writers have this goal: to transfer an image from their minds into the minds of readers. And they want readers to be as struck by that image as possible.Â  If a writer sends me â€œcat,â€ I may receive the word, but just receiving isnâ€™t good enough. I may receive it and forget about it a moment later. Writers want to transfer images, and they want those images to STICK. Which means they must describe those images in a way thatâ€™s as vivid and sensual as possible. (Sensual, because we experience through our senses, so if you can con a reader into believing heâ€™s seeing, hearing, tasting, smelling or touching, you win.) Most writing-rules boil down to this: â€œlick the reader.â€ If you lick his face, heâ€™ll remember you.</p>

<p>For instance, we avoid the passive-voice because it doesnâ€™t lick the readerâ€™s face. (Though, perhaps, the readerâ€™s face is licked.) When I first wrote the paragraph two places above this one, I started it â€œWhich means images must be describedâ€¦â€ itâ€™s hard to imagine images being described. Being described by <em>whom?</em> The easiest sentences to see are the ones in which an agent does something TO something. So I rewrote it as â€œthey [the writers] must describeâ€¦â€ Itâ€™s still not great, because â€œdescribeâ€ is a weak verb â€“ one that doesnâ€™t evoke a strong image â€“ but at least Iâ€™m evoking the idea of a writer DOING SOMETHING and not of something just happening.</p>

