<p>A person can point to a tree, and a person can run, but a person canâ€™t dangerously. Itâ€™s impossible to imagine dangerously. There is no such thing as dangerously. Itâ€™s possible to imagine dancing dangerously or holding a knife dangerously, but these phrases put a burdon on the reader. He must first evoke â€œholding a knife.â€ Then he must add â€œdangerouslyâ€ to it. You run the risk that he wonâ€™t: that heâ€™ll just mush everything together into some vague â€œunderstandingâ€ of what youâ€™re trying to evoke. The worst thing a writer can achieve is his reader â€œgetting the point.â€ <strong>You donâ€™t want the reader to get the point. You want to lick his face.</strong></p>

